    \arrow[no head, from=1-4, to=2-5]
    \arrow[dashed, no head, from=2-2, to=1-3]
    \arrow[dashed, no head, from=2-3, to=1-4]
    \arrow[dashed, no head, from=2-4, to=1-5]
\end{tikzcd}
</latex-image>
</image>
</figure>



<p>
Alternatively, to notice the `criss-cross' pattern it helps to write the vectors using columns:
<me>
\begin{bmatrix}
  u_1 \\ u_2\\ u_3
\end{bmatrix}
\times
\begin{bmatrix}
  v_1 \\ v_2\\ v_3
\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}
  u_2v_3 - u_3v_2 \\ u_3v_1 - u_1v_3\\ u_1v_2-u_2v_1
\end{bmatrix}
</me>.
</p>

<p>
Here are three examples which also showcase properties of the cross product.
</p>


<example xml:id="ex-cross">
<statement>
<p>
If <m>\vect{u} = [3, 1, 2]</m> and <m>\vect{v} = [5, 0, 4]</m>, then
<me>
\vect{u} \times \vect{v} = [1(4) - 2(0), 2(5) - 3(4), 3(0) - 1(5)] = [4, -2, -5]
</me>
and
<me>
\vect{v}\times\vect{u} = [0(2) - 4(1), 4(3) - 5(2), 5(1) - 0(3)] = [-4, 2, 5]
</me>.
Notice that <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v} = - \vect{v} \times \vect{u}</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

