<example xml:id="ex-dot-and-cross">
  <title>(Finding cross product)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Find <m>\vect{u}\cdot (\vect{u}\times\vect{v})</m> and <m>\vect{v}\cdot (\vect{u}\times\vect{v})</m> 
for <m>\vect{u} = [3, 1, 2]</m> and <m>\vect{v} = [5, 0, 4]</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
  <p>
  From the previous example, we know 
<m>\vect{u} \times\vect{v} = [4, -2, -5]</m>. So
<me>
\vect{u}\cdot(\vect{u}\times\vect{v}) = [3, 1, 2] \cdot [4, -2, -5] = 12-2-10 = 0,
</me>
<me>
\vect{v}\cdot (\vect{u}\times\vect{v}) = [5, 0, 4] \cdot [4, -2, -5] = 20+0-20 = 0.
</me>
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<example xml:id="ex-uxuiszero">
<statement>
<p>If <m>\vect{u} = [3, 1, 2]</m>, then
<me>
\vect{u}\times \vect{u} = [2-2, 6-6, 3-3] = [0, 0, 0] = \vect{0}.
</me></p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
The next theorem lists the main properties of the cross product.
</p>


<theorem xml:id="thm-cross-product-props">
  <title>(Properties of cross products)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v}, \vect{w} \in\R^3</m> and <m>c\in \R</m>. Then
<ol>
<li>
<p><m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v} = -\vect{v} \times \vect{u}\quad</m> (anti-commutativity)
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\vect{u} \cdot (\vect{u}\times \vect{v}) = \vect{v} \cdot(\vect{u}\times \vect{v} ) = 0</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\vect{u} \times \vect{u} = \vect{0}</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\vect{u} \times \vect{0} = \vect{0} \times\vect{u} = \vect{0}</m>
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>\vect{u}\times (\vect{v} + \vect{w})=\vect{u}\times \vect{v} + \vect{u} \times \vect{w}\quad</m> (left distributivity)
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>(\vect{u} + \vect{v})\times \vect{w} = \vect{u} \times\vect{w} + \vect{v} \times \vect{w}\quad</m> (right distributivity)
</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><m>(c\vect{u})\times \vect{v} = \vect{u} \times (c\vect{v}) = c(\vect{u}\times \vect{v})</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</theorem>

<p>
Property 2 says that <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v}</m> is orthogonal to <m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m>. 
We will prove Properties 2, 3, and 5.
</p>

<proof>
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u} = [u_1, u_2, u_3], \vect{v} = [v_1, v_2, v_3]</m> and <m>\vect{w} = [w_1, w_2, w_3]</m>. 
Property 2 holds since
<md>
<mrow>
\vect{u} \cdot (\vect{u}\times \vect{v}) \amp  = [u_1, u_2, u_3]\cdot [u_2v_3 - u_3v_2, u_3v_1 - u_1v_3, u_1v_2-u_2v_1] \\
\amp  = u_1u_2v_3 - u_1u_3v_2 + u_2u_3v_1 - u_2u_1v_3 + u_3u_1v_2 - u_3u_2v_1  \\
\amp  =0;
</mrow>
</md>
the calculation that <m>\vect{v} \cdot(\vect{u}\times \vect{v}) = 0</m> is similar. We can deduce Property 3 
from Property 1 by observing that
<me>
\vect{u} \times \vect{u} = -\vect{u} \times \vect{u},
</me>
so <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{u} = 0</m>. Finally, the proof of Property 5 is that
<md>
<mrow>
\amp\vect{u}\times (\vect{v} + \vect{w}) \\
\amp  = [u_1, u_2, u_3]\times [v_1 + w_1, v_2 + w_2, v_3 + w_3]                                                   \\
\amp  = [u_2(v_3 + w_3) - u_3(v_2 + w_2), u_3(v_1 + w_1)- u_1(v_3 + w_3), \\
\amp\qquad\qquad u_1(v_2 + w_2) - u_2(v_1 + w_1)]       \\
\amp  = [u_2v_3 - u_3v_2, u_3v_1 - u_1v_3, u_1v_2 - u_2v_1] \\
\amp\quad\qquad+ [u_2w_3 - u_3w_2, u_3w_1 - u_1w_3, u_1w_2 - u_2w_1] \\
\amp  = \vect{u} \times \vect{v} + \vect{u} \times \vect{w}.
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</proof>

<p>
Importantly, the cross product is not associative! This means that, for 
<m>\vect{u}, \vect{v}, \vect{w} \in \R^3</m>,
<me>
(\vect{u}\times \vect{v})\times \vect{w} \ne \vect{u} \times (\vect{v}\times \vect{w})
</me>.
For example, if <m>\vect{u} = [1, 1, 0], \vect{v} = [0, 1, 1], \vect{w} = [0, 0, 1]</m>, then
<me>
(\vect{u}\times \vect{v})\times \vect{w} = [1, -1, 1] \times [0, 0, 1] =[-1, -1, 0]
</me>
while
<me>
\vect{u} \times (\vect{v}\times \vect{w}) = [1, 1, 0] \times [1, 0, 0] = [0, 0, -1]
</me>.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-cross-product-algebra">
  <title>(Simplifying a cross product)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Simplify <m>(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) \times (\vect{u} - \vect{v})</m> using the properties in the theorem.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
  <p>
  We have
<md>
<mrow>
(\vect{u} + \vect{v}) \times (\vect{u} - \vect{v}) \amp  =  (\vect{u} + \vect{v}) \times \vect{u} + (\vect{u} + \vect{v}) \times (-\vect{v})\quad \text{(Property 5)} \\
\amp  = (\vect{u} + \vect{v}) \times \vect{u} - (\vect{u} + \vect{v})\times\vect{v}                               \quad \text{(Property 7)}           \\
\amp  = \vect{u}\times \vect{u} + \vect{v} \times \vect{u} - (\vect{u} \times \vect{v} + \vect{v}\times \vect{v}) \quad \text{(Property 6)}           \\
\amp  = \vect{v} \times \vect{u} - \vect{u} \times \vect{v}                                                       \quad \text{(Property 3)}        \\
\amp  = - 2\vect{u}\times \vect{v}.                                                                               \quad \text{(Property 1)} 
</mrow>
</md>
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<p>
Recall that <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v}</m> is orthogonal to both <m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m>. 
If <m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m> are not parallel, then the set of linear combinations of 
<m>\vect{u}</m> and <m>\vect{v}</m> is a plane in <m>\R^3</m>. The cross product <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v}</m> 
must be orthogonal to this plane, so there are only two choices for its direction. This is show in 
<xref ref="fig-plane_normals"/>: the two orthogonal vectors are the upwards normal vector and the 
downwards normal vector, drawn in red.
</p>



