<p>
  So the cross product can only point in one of two directions, but which one is it?
</p>

<assemblage xml:id="right-hand-rule">
  <title>(Right-hand rule)</title>
  <p>
The direction of <m>\vect{u} \times \vect{v}</m> is given by the right hand rule:
<ol>
<li>
<p>Point the fingers of your right hand straight in the direction of <m>\vect{u}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Curl fingers towards the direction of <m>\vect{v}</m>.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Your thumb points in the direction of <m>\vect{u}\times \vect{v}</m>.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</p>
<figure xml:id="fig-rhr">
<caption>The right hand rule</caption>
<!--RHR pic needed-->
</figure>
</assemblage>


<p>
Now that we know the direction of <m>\vect{u}\times \vect{v}</m>, we want to calculate its magnitude. 
First, it will help to have the following fact (we leave the proof as an exercise).
</p>


<assemblage xml:id="fact-length-of-cross">
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^3</m>. Then we have
<md>
  \|\vect{u} \times\vect{v}\|^2 = \|\vect{u}\|^2\|\vect{v}\|^2 - |\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v}|^2
</md>.
</p>
</assemblage>

<p>
Now we can calculate the length of a cross product.
</p>


<theorem xml:id="Thm-lengpara">
  <title>(Length of cross product)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^3</m>, and <m>\theta</m> be the angle between <m>\vect{u}</m> and 
<m>\vect{v}</m> such that <m>0 \le \theta \le \pi</m>. Then
<me>
\|\vect{u} \times \vect{v}\| = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\sin\theta
</me>.
</p>
</statement>

<proof>
<p>
By the boxed fact above and the geometric formula for the dot product,
<md>
<mrow>
\|\vect{u} \times\vect{v}\|^2 \amp  = \|\vect{u}\|^2\|\vect{v}\|^2 - |\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v}|^2              \\
\amp  = \|\vect{u}\|^2\|\vect{v}\|^2 - |\|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\cos\theta|^2 \\
\amp  = \|\vect{u}\|^2\|\vect{v}\|^2(1-\cos^2\theta)                          \\
\amp  = \|\vect{u}\|^2\|\vect{v}\|^2\sin^2\theta
</mrow>
</md>.
Since <m>0 \le \theta\le \pi</m>, we have <m>\sin\theta \ge 0</m>, and so taking square roots gives the 
result.
</p>
</proof>
</theorem>

<example xml:id="ex-length-of-cross">
  <title>(Calculating length of cross product)</title>
  
  
<statement>
<p>
Suppose <m>\vect{u}, \vect{v} \in \R^3</m> are such that <m>\|\vect{u}\| = \sqrt{6}, \|\vect{v}\| = \sqrt{35}</m>, and 
<m>\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v} = 14</m>. Find <m>\|\vect{u} \times \vect{v}\|</m>.
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
  <p>
We first calculate that
<me>
\cos\theta = \frac{\vect{u}\cdot\vect{v}}{\|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|} = \frac{14}{\sqrt{6}\sqrt{35}} = \frac{14}{\sqrt{210}}
</me>.
Then <m>\sin^2\theta = 1- \cos^2\theta = \frac{1}{15}</m>, so <m>\sin\theta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{15}}</m>. (We used the 
  positive square root since <m>0\le\theta\le\pi</m>). Finally,
<me>
\|\vect{u} \times \vect{v}\| = \|\vect{u}\|\|\vect{v}\|\sin\theta = \sqrt{\frac{210}{15}} = \sqrt{14}.
</me>
</p>
</solution>
</example>



